A sculpture that is part of the Elgin Marbles has been unveiled in Russia, after a secret deal with the British Museum, in a move that has infuriated Greece.

The headless statue of Greek river-god Ilissos went on display today at the State Hermitage Museum in St Petersburg as part of its 250th anniversary celebrations.

But the move has prompted a furious diplomatic row with Greece, as the British Museum allowed one of the classical marble sculptures leave the UK for the first time - in a shroud of secrecy. 

