However, Mr MacGregor ruled out a return, arguing last month that they gave 'maximum public benefit' by staying in London.

The 7th Earl of Elgin, Thomas Bruce, had the Parthenon Marble sculptures removed while serving as the British ambassador to the Ottoman Empire from 1799 to 1803.

In 1801, the Earl claimed to have obtained a permit from the Ottoman authorities to remove pieces from the Parthenon and his agents took half of the surviving sculptures and had them shipped to Britain.

In Greece, however, the Scottish aristocrat was accused of looting.

The marbles were bought by the British government to be displayed in the British Museum.

